com.mvohm.quadruple.test

Class TestData

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.mvohm.quadruple.test.TestData

  • public class TestData
extends Object
    Data sets for testing substantial public methods of Quadruple. Provide coverage for all the code of the methods and some corner cases (except most trivial ones that don't require special testing). All the data are static arrays of Strings representing numeric values, generally with precision of 120 decimal digits. Every array contains data for testing a certain operation, like the addition or a conversion from one type to another. The arrays consist of groups, each group of two (for unary operations and conversions) or three (for binary operations) items represents a test case. The first item of a pair or the two first items of a triplet are the input operands for the corresponding operation, and the last one is a value that should be the result of the operation. In most cases, the expected result may be determined by the code that performs testing, in such cases there may be null or an empty string instead of the expected value, e.g. 
     "3.5", "4.5", "8",   // for addition: 3.5 + 4.5 = 8
 "1", "2", null,      // the testing code will find
                      // that the result should be 3
 ...
 "-1.2345e2345", "",  // for the conversion from Quadruple to double,
                      // the result should be Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY
    In cases where the operation being tested, when applied to the given operand(s), should throw an exception, the word "Error" is used instead of the expected result, to inform the testing code about the fact that throwing an exception is the expected behavior of the operation.
    There are two sorts of strings that are interpreted by the testing code in special ways:
    • If the first string of the group starts with "//", it is considered to be a comment and can be printed by the testing code to the console, depending on the code and/or the execution mode, the subsequent items of the group are ignored in this case.
    • If the first string of the group equals "$_STOP_$", it is interpreted as an instruction to quit the test execution.

      • basic_Q2S_conversionData

        static String[] basic_Q2S_conversionData
        A data set for testing Quadruple.toString().
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the number to be converted and the expected result. Actually, in this data set the expected result can be correctly deduced by the test code in all cases, so all the odd items are nulls.
        The number of items must be even.

      • basic_Q2D_conversionData

        static String[] basic_Q2D_conversionData
        A data set for testing Quadruple.doubleValue().
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the number to be converted, and the expected result. The latter is actually needed only in the cases when the value can't be represented as BigDecimal, which is used as the type of findExpectedResult() in Conversion_Q2T_Tester.
        The number of items must be even.

      • basic_Q2BD_conversionData

        static String[] basic_Q2BD_conversionData
        A data set for testing Quadruple.bigDecimalValue()
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the number to be converted, and the expected result. For the values that are not valid values for BigDecimal, the method is expected to throw an exception. The word "Error" is used as the expected result in such cases. For all other values, the expected results can be evaluated by the testing code, thus the data contains nulls instead of expected values.
        The number of items must be even.

      • special_S2Q_conversionSata

        static String[] special_S2Q_conversionSata
        An auxiliary data set that can be used for testing or debugging Quadruple.bigDecimalValue() with some values of a special interest.
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the value to be used for testing or debugging the method, and a string representation of the expected result
        The number of items must be even.

      • basic_S2Q_conversionData

        static String[] basic_S2Q_conversionData
        A data set for testing Quadruple.assign(String value) or the constructor that accepts a String
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the value to be assigned, and the value that a Quadruple instance is expected to have after the assignment. In most cases the expected value for a sample can be evaluated by the testing code, so nulls are used instead of the expected values.
        Since some special String values can be used as the assignment arguments to designate certain Quadruple values ("min_value", "max_value", etc.), such strings are accompanied with string representations of the corresponding Quadruple values.
        The samples of knowingly unacceptable input strings that are expected to cause an exception are accompanied with the word "error".
        The number of items must be even.

      • basic_BD2Q_conversionData

        static String[] basic_BD2Q_conversionData
        A data set for testing Quadruple.assign(BigDecimal value) or the constructor that accepts a BigDecimal
        Each data sample consists of two strings: a string representation of the value to be assigned, and the value that a Quadruple instance is expected to have after the assignment. For any BigDecimal value, the corresponding Quadruple value can be evaluated by the testing code, so nulls are used as the second items for all samples.
        thus the data contains nulls instead of expected values.
        The number of items must be even.

      • basicAdditionData

        static String[] basicAdditionData
        A data set for testing the addition.
        Each data sample consists of three strings: two operands and the expected result of their addition.
        For any pair of the operands, the corresponding result can be evaluated by the testing code, thus the data contains nulls instead of the values of the expected results.
        The number of items must be divisible by 3.

      • specialSubtractionData

        The number of items must be divisible by 3.

      • basicSubtractionData

        static String[] basicSubtractionData
        A data set for testing the subtraction.
        Each data sample consists of three strings: minuend, subtrahend, and the expected value of their difference.
        For any pair of the operands, the corresponding result can be evaluated by the testing code, thus the data contains nulls instead of the values of the expected results.
        The number of items must be divisible by 3.

      • basicMultiplicationData

        static String[] basicMultiplicationData
        A data set for testing the multiplication.
        Each data sample consists of three strings: two factors and the expected value of their product.
        For most of the pairs of the operands, the corresponding result can be evaluated by the testing code, thus the data in such cases contains nulls instead of the values of the expected results.
        Exceptions are cases where the product is subnormal, since subnormal values contain fewer bits in the mantissa than normal values, so the relative error of subnormal values can be much larger than the standard error threshold.
        The number of items must be divisible by 3.

      • specialDivisionData

        A data set for testing or debugging the division at some specific values that may be of special interest.
        Each data sample consists of three strings: two operands and the expected result of their addition.
        The number of items must be divisible by 3.

      • basicDivisionData

        static String[] basicDivisionData
        A data set for testing the division.
        Each data sample consists of three strings: the dividend, the divisor, and the expected value of their quotient.
        For most of the pairs of the operands, the corresponding result can be evaluated by the testing code, thus the data in such cases contains nulls instead of the values of the expected results.
        Exceptions are cases where the quotient is subnormal, since subnormal values contain fewer bits in the mantissa than normal values, so the relative error of subnormal values can be much larger than the standard error threshold.
        The number of items must be divisible by 3.
